name: AHREUM
bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up the sport when she was in the sixth grade at primary school. (mbcsportsplus.com, 24 Nov 2017)'), ('Reason', "Her older brother wanted to take up the sport but the siblings' father said he could only do it if his younger sister joined in. So she started riding with her brother, discovered she enjoyed it and kept it up. (mbcsportsplus.com, 24 Nov 2017)"), ('Debut', '2009 for Republic of Korea (mbcsportsplus.com, 24 Nov 2017)'), ('Coach', 'Jeon Jae-Hyo [club], KOR; Um In-Young [national], KOR; Sean Eadie [national], AUS (kbmaeil.com, 27 Jun 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (mbcsportsplus.com, 24 Nov 2017)'), ('Memorable', "Competing at the 2010 Asian Games in Guangzhou, People's Republic of China. (mbcsportsplus.com, 24 Nov 2017)"), ('Awards', 'She was named Best Cyclist at the 2017 and 2018 KBS National Championships in Yangyang, Republic of Korea. (kbmaeil.com, 27 Jun 2018; yonhapnews.co.kr, 30 Jun 2017) She was named Best Athlete at the 2017 Sangju City Athletics Awards in the Republic of Korea. (anewsa.com, 22 Dec 2017)She received an Excellence Award at the Korean Sport and Olympic Committee Athletics Awards in 2015. (newsis.com, 10 Feb 2015)She received the 2015 Grand Prize of the Year at the Night of the Cyclists in the Republic of Korea. (moneyweek.co.kr, 20 Jan 2015)She was named the 2014 Best Athlete by the Jeonbuk Sports Council in the Republic of Korea. (jjan.kr, 10 Dec 2014)She was named Best Cyclist at the Korean Cycling Federation Awards in 2009 and 2012. (najutoday.co.kr, 22 Jan 2010; naver.com, 29 Jul 2012)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralCOMPETITION FIRSTSHaving claimed gold in the individual time trial at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea, she triumphed in the road race four years later at the 2018 Games in Indonesia to become the first athlete from any nation to have finished on top of the podium in both events at the Asian Games. She also won the individual time trial at the 2018 Asian Games to become the first athlete to have claimed gold in both events at the same edition of the Games. (SportsDeskOnline, 31 Aug 2018; asahi.com, 29 Aug 2018)NATIONAL FIRSTShe became the first female Korean cyclist to win an event at a round of the World Cup when she claimed a victory in the points race at the 2011/12 event in Astana, Kazakhstan. (SportsDeskOnline, 30 Jun 2018; mbcsportsplus.com, 24 Nov 2017; chosun.com, 07 Nov 2017) '), ('Hero', 'Korean track cyclist Cho Ho-Sung, coach Kim Yong-Mi. (bikewhat.com, 01 Apr 2012; segye.com, 27 Jul 2013)'), ('Influence', 'Her parents. (mbcsportsplus.com, 24 Nov 2017)'), ('Relatives', 'Her older sister Na Hee-Kyung was also a cyclist. On the track she won a silver medal in the team pursuit at the 2015 National Championships and on the road she competed in three consecutive road races at the national championships between 2011 and 2013. (jeollailbo.com, 28 Oct 2015; SportsDeskOnline, 02 Mar 2016; mbcsportsplus.com, 24 Nov 2017)'), ('Injuries', "She was knocked unconscious in a crash during the points race at the 2010 Asian Games in Guangzhou, People's Republic of China. She suffered no long term injuries. name: Salwa
bio: [('Beginning', 'Her mother was a sprinter at school and Salwa quickly discovered she also had an ability to sprint. "As kids, we would run around and play, and the other kids would say I was fast." (iaaf.org, 21 Jul 2015)'), ('Reason', 'She won her first race at age 11 over 100m, and later won over 400m. "When I finished I felt so bad that I thought I never wanted to run another 400m again. My teacher insisted that I would make a good 400m runner, so I had no choice but to carry on. I am so grateful I listened to my teacher." (iaaf.org, 21 Jul 2015)'), ('Coach', 'John George Obeya [personal], NGA, from 2016 (iaaf.org, 10 Aug 2017)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralYOUNGESTShe became the youngest female athlete to win a medal in 400m at the world championships, when she took silver at the 2017 edition in London, England, at age 19 years and 78 days. (makingofchamps.com, 10 Aug 2017; SportsDeskOnline, 14 May 2018)NATIONAL FIRSTShe was the first female athlete from Bahrain to win a gold medal at the world youth championships, when she triumphed in the 400m final at the 2015 edition of the tournament in Cali, Colombia. She also became the first Asian female athlete to win a medal in 400m at the world championships, when she took silver at the 2017 edition in London, England. (albawaba.com, 19 Jul 2015; athleticsasia.org, 10 Aug 2017; SportsDeskOnline, 14 May 2018)NIGERIA TO BAHRAINShe was born in Nigeria to a Bahraini father and Nigerian mother, and moved with her family to Bahrain as a child. (iaaf.org, 21 Jul 2015) '), ('Hero', 'Bahraini sprinter Rakia Al-Gassra, US sprinter Sanya Richards-Ross, US sprinter Allyson Felix. name: NUNNAPAT
bio: [('Beginning', 'She was initially introduced to the sport at age 10 through her uncle, and later began serious training in 2008. (old.fai.org, 29 Jul 2013)'), ('Reason', '"At age 10, my uncle came to visit our home and brought his paramotor over. I played around on it, but I dared not start the engine. I started practising seriously at age 20, learning the basics and flying off a small hill. In 2011 I was able to join the national team." (mgronline.com, 02 Nov 2015; old.fai.org, 29 Jul 2013)'), ('Ambition', 'Outside of sport, she aims to work for the police or the military in Thailand after graduating from university. (mgronline.com, 02 Nov 2015)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralEARLY DAYSShe dreamt of flying since she was young, although her mother did not initially support her involvement in the sport due to its potential dangers. "My mum saw me compete in Chonburi [in Thailand] once and was shocked to see my flying because she was worried it would be dangerous. So I decided to take her up to the hill and had her put on the paragliding gear before letting her fly on her own. I wanted her to understand the feeling that I get when I am in the sky and can see the beautiful view below and all the people supporting me from the ground. She started understanding more and started supporting me more and with her support, I managed to succeed on an international level and became world champion. I am glad that I could make my mother and everyone else proud of me." (mgronline.com, 02 Nov 2015) HIGHER EDUCATIONShe initially took a nursing course before moving to Ramkhamhaeng University in Bangkok, Thailand, to study science. She then switched to political science in order to have more time for paragliding. "At first, I passed the nursing entrance exam and was studying nursing. However, I was concerned about having no time to practice so after two years I decided to change university and my field of study. I moved to Ramkhamhaeng University and decided to study science, but I did not have enough time to practice and attend lab classes at the same time. I then decided to change my field of study again to political science, which gave me enough time to study and train. Although I wasted time in the beginning it has worked out well for me." (mgronline.com, 02 Nov 2015) '), ('Nickname', 'Bee (nationmultimedia.com, 22 May 2017)'), ('Education', 'Political Science - Ramkhamhaeng University, Bangkok, THA'), ('Languages', 'Thai'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationResultWorld Accuracy Championship1Individual Accuracy2017Vlore, ALB221Individual Accuracy2015Homyel, BLR111Team Accuracy2015Homyel, BLR2215Individual Accuracy2015Homyel, BLR117Team Accuracy2017Vlore, ALB8921Individual Accuracy2017Vlore, ALB22World Games2Individual Accuracy2013Cali, COL816Asian-Oceanic Accuracy Championships1Team Accuracy2018Sara Buri, THA3Individual Accuracy2018Sara Buri, THA17314Individual Accuracy2018Sara Buri, THA173Asian Accuracy Championship1Individual Accuracy2014Ranau, MAS5062Individual Accuracy2016Taldykorgan, KAZ6478Individual Accuracy2014Ranau, MAS50616Individual Accuracy2016Taldykorgan, KAZ647South East Asian Games2Team Accuracy2011Indonesia68922Team Cross Country2011Indonesia16923Distance Team2011Indonesia4704Individual Accuracy2011Indonesia89512Cross Country Individual2011Indonesia19713Distance Individual2011Indonesia149World Pilots Ranking Accuracy (as of 01 Aug 2018)2Accuracy Individual Ranking201818548Accuracy Individual Ranking2018185')]

bio: [('Beginning', 'She began the sport in 2000 as a hurdler and heptathlete. (Nigeria Athletics Incorporated Facebook page, 09 May 2014)'), ('Reason', 'She loved running. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2016)'), ('Debut', '2014 for Bahrain, in Doha, Qatar (Athlete, 13 Aug 2016)'), ('Memorable', 'Competing at the 2016 World Indoor Championships in Portland, OR, United States of America. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2016)'), ('Awards', 'She was named All-Athletics.com Athlete of the Year in 2014 in Asia. (ATL FM Sports Facebook page, 05 Jan 2015)'), ('Additional Information', "GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTShe was the first athlete from Bahrain to win a world indoor championships title when she won the women's 400m final at the 2016 championships in Portland, OR, United States of America. (iaaf.org, 20 Mar 2016; SportsDeskOnline, 26 Jul 2018)NIGERIA TO BAHRAINShe was born in Lagos, Nigeria, but switched allegiance from Nigeria to Bahrain in early 2014. In her first race for her new country she set a national record, a personal best and clocked the fastest 400m hurdles time of the year at that time, with a 54.59 seconds victory. Her move to Bahrain was unknown to Athletics Federation of Nigeria [AFN] president Solomon Ogba, who lodged a complaint with the International Association of Athletics Federations [IAAF], insisting her move was out of process. However, because Adekoya had never formally registered with the AFN, the country could not block the move. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2016; 9jamirror Facebook page, 06 Sep 2015; iaaf.org, 09 May 2014; sportswithnee.com, 10 May 2014; vanguardngr.com, 07 Jun 2014; athletics-africa.com, 16 May 2014) "), ('Hero', 'US runner Sanya Richards-Ross. name: Iman
bio: [('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONALITY AND NAME CHANGEShe was born in Nigeria under the name Endurance Essien Udoh. She was part of the Cross River State Athletics programme in Nigeria but never made the national team at any level. Due to increased opportunities to compete at international level she switched to Bahrain and began competing under the name Iman Isa Jassim. "I didn\'t allow my talent to die in Nigeria as a state athlete only. [With Bahrain] I\'ve gone to a lot of competitions that if I was in Nigeria I wouldn\'t have done." name: NICOL ANN
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began playing squash at age five. (nst.com.my, 08 Jul 2017)'), ('Reason', "One of her father's friends built the first public squash centre in Penang, Malaysia. Her older sisters Lianne and Cheryl played the sport, and she began going along with them. (squashstars.com, 25 Dec 2012; wispa.net, 02 Nov 2006)"), ('Coach', 'Peter Genever [national], GBR; Liz Irving [personal], AUS, from 2003 (thestar.com.my, 26 Mar 2018, 29 Mar 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the Olympic Games. (thestar.com.my, 19 Apr 2018)'), ('Awards', "She was one of six athletes chosen to carry the Commonwealth Games Federation [CGF] flag at the opening ceremony of the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, Scotland. An athlete was chosen from each region of the Commonwealth, and David represented the eight Asian nations competing at the Games. (bernama.com.my, 11 Jun 2014)She was named the Women's Squash Association [WSA] Player of the Year for six consecutive years between 2005 and 2010. She also won the award in 2012. (wsaworldtour.com, 2013; squashmagazine.com, 2012)She was inducted into the World Squash Federation Hall of Fame in November 2011, becoming the first active player to be receive the honour. (worldsquash.org, 10 Nov 2011)She was voted Malaysia's Sportswoman of the Year for the 10th time in 2014. (worldsquash.org, 10 Nov 2011; malaysiandigest.com, 29 Apr 2015)In 2008 she was presented with the Order of Merit by the king of Malaysia. (nicoldavidonline.com, 05 May 2009)She was one of the first entrants into Malaysia's SportExcel Hall of Fame in July 2002. (The Star, 09 Jul 2002)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTSShe became the first Malaysian squash player to win a gold medal at the Commonwealth Games when she claimed victory in singles at the 2010 Games in Delhi, India. She also became the first Malaysian squash player to win gold at the Asian Games when she placed first in singles at the 1998 Games in Bangkok. (SportsDeskOnline, 26 Jun 2018)OTHER ACTIVITIESIn December 2008 she set up an online social media news, blog and entertainment portal called Squash Stars. The purpose of the platform is to promote women squash players with the ultimate aim of promoting the sport for the Olympic Games. (Squash Stars Facebook page, 28 Oct 2017; paultan.org, 10 Jan 2018)TURNING POINTShe believes relocating to the Netherlands in 2003 to join up with Australian coach Liz Irving really launched her career. "The move to Amsterdam got me to go back a step and break everything down from scratch. I started from pretty much zero to build my technique and my movement and learn how to volley well. In the seniors it was a whole different ball game as opposed to being in the juniors. That was my turning point to be where I am right now." (nytimes.com, 18 Sep 2014) '), ('Hero', 'US basketball player Michael Jordan, Swiss tennis player Roger Federer. (princesquash.com, 29 Jan 2014; thestar.com.my, 16 Apr 2018)'), ('Influence', 'Her parents. (princesquash.com, 29 Jan 2014)'), ('Relatives', 'Her sisters Lianne and Cheryl have both played squash at national level in Malaysia. Her father represented the state of Penang in athletics, football and hockey. (nytimes.com, 18 Sep 2014; nurain4e.blogspot.com, 30 Sep 2013)'), ('Nickname', 'The Smiling Assassin (squashtalk.com 05 May 2009; issuu.com, 04 Feb 2015)'), ('Injuries', 'In early 2018 she suffered hamstring and adductor strain injuries, which caused her to miss the British Open in May that year. (thestar.com.my, 05 May 2018)In December 2016 a hamstring injury meant that she was unable to compete at the Malaysian Doubles Open in Kuala Lumpur. (thestar.com.my, 19 Dec 2016)In September 2015 she was forced to miss the Macau Open due to a calf injury. (thestar.com.my, 12 Sep 2015)'), ('Education', 'University of Nottingham Malaysia Campus, Malaysia'), ('Languages', 'English, Malay'), ('Hobbies', 'Reading, travelling, world cuisine, art, drawing. (nst.com.my, 08 Jul 2017; star2.com, 22 Aug 2017; psaworldtour.com, 2018)'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationAsian Games1Singles2014Incheon, KOR1Team2014Incheon, KOR1Singles2010Guangzhou, CHN1Team2010Guangzhou, CHN1Singles2006Doha, QAT1Singles1998Bangkok, THA2Singles2002Busan, KORWorld Games1Singles2013Cali, COL3Singles2017Wroclaw, POLWorld Championships1Singles2014Cairo, EGY1Singles2012Camana Bay, CAY1Singles2011Rotterdam, NED1Singles2010Sharm El Sheikh, EGY1Singles2009Amsterdam, NED1Singles2008Manchester, GBR1Singles2006Belfast, GBR1Singles2005Hong Kong, CHN3Singles2013George Town, MAS3Singles2004Kuala Lumpur, MAS3Singles2003Hong Kong, CHN5Singles2017Manchester, GBR5Singles2016El Gouna, EGY5Singles2015Kuala Lumpur, MAS9Singles2007Madrid, ESPWorld Team Championships2Team2014Niagara-on-the-Lake, ON, CAN3Team2012Nimes, FRA3Team2010Palmerston North, NZL3Team2008Cairo, EGY3Team2006Edmonton, AB, CAN5Team2004Amsterdam, NED6Team2016Paris, FRAWorld Doubles Championships4Doubles W2004Chennai, IND8Doubles W2017Wroclaw, POLAsian Individual Championships1Singles2015Kuwait City, KUW1Singles2011George Town, MAS1Singles2010Chennai, IND1Singles2008Kuwait1Team2008Kuwait1Singles2006Taipei, TPE3Team2010Chennai, INDSouth East Asian Games1Singles2001Kuala Lumpur, MAS1Team2001Kuala Lumpur, MASCommonwealth Games1Singles2014Glasgow, GBR1Singles2010Delhi, IND2Doubles X2002Manchester, GBR3Doubles X2010Delhi, IND4Singles2018Gold Coast, QLD, AUSWorld Ranking (as of 01 Aug 2018)9Singles2018')]

(SportsDeskOnline, 31 Aug 2018; indiawest.com, 29 Aug 2018)EXTRA TOESShe was born with six toes on each foot. "I have been competing with a lot of pain physically. The width of the shoes has an impact on how my foot lands and the lack of expansion around the edges results in discomfort. I have tried multiple brands but unfortunately my condition is unique and none of the shoes are customised for something like this. Apart from the pain, of course, the shoes themselves don\'t last long." (channelnewsasia.com, 30 Aug 2018; thenewsminute.com, 04 Aug 2016) '), ('Influence', 'Coach Subhash Sarkar. (thenewsminute.com, 04 Aug 2016)'), ('Injuries', 'Despite suffering from extreme toothache that required her to apply heavy taping to her jaw and chin she won the gold medal in the heptathlon at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (bbc.co.uk, 01 Sep 2018)She struggled with back pain following the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea. The injury continued to trouble her for the next three years and she required a month-long break from training after the 2017 World Championships in London, England. name: HIDILYN
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began weightlifting at age 11 in Zamboanga, Philippines. (blogs.wsj.com, 24 Jul 2012)'), ('Reason', '"My cousins were weightlifters and I saw them lifting, in fact they were not lifting barbells, it was wood that looked like ipil-ipil [lead tree]. I thought, \'What are they doing? It looks like fun\', and that\'s how I started." (rappler.com, 07 Mar 2016; blogs.wsj.com, 24 Jul 2012)'), ('Coach', 'Antonio Agustin Jr. [national] (sunstar.com.ph, 22 Sep 2017)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a gold medal at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (philstar.com, 16 Aug 2016)'), ('Awards', 'She received the Outstanding Young Men [TOYM] Award [presented to both male and female recipients] for 2017 by the Senate of the Philippines. (iwf.net, 14 Mar 2018)She was named the 2016 Athlete of the Year by the Philippine Sportswriters Association [PSA]. (bworldonline.com, 19 May 2017)She received a plaque of recognition from the Armed Forces of the Philippines [AFP] in recognition of her silver medal at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (gmanetwork.com, 22 Aug 2016)She was flag bearer for the Philippines at the opening ceremony of the 2012 Olympic Games in London. (olympic.org, Aug 2012)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTIn 2016 she became the first female athlete representing the Philippines to win a medal at the Olympic Games when she claimed silver in weightlifting [53kg] in Rio de Janeiro. The previous year [2015] she had become the first female weightlifter representing the Philippines to finish on the podium at the world championships when she took three bronze medals in Houston, TX, United States of America. (SportsDeskOnline, 07 Aug 2016)BUSINESS OWNERIn 2017 she opened a weightlifting gym in Zamboanga, Philippines. "My main goal is to help out kids in my hometown and realise their dream in weightlifting. This sport could change their lives and hopefully they could become just like me in the future." name: HSINGCHUN
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began weightlifting in middle school. (parenting.com.tw, 01 Nov 2016)'), ('Reason', 'She became interested in the sport after finishing first in weightlifting at a school sports meeting. (parenting.com.tw, 01 Nov 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Lin Jing-Neng [national], TPE (businesstoday.com.tw, 13 Mar 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win gold at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia and the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (cna.com.tw, 28 Apr 2018; city543.com, 15 Sep 2017; udn.com, 05 Mar 2017)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning bronze in the 58kg category at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (udn.com, 05 Mar 2017)'), ('Awards', "She was named Chinese Taipei's flag bearer for the opening ceremony of the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (focustaiwan.tw, 10 Aug 2018)In 2017 she received the Order of Brilliant Star in Chinese Taipei. (focustaiwan.tw, 07 Sep 2017; taiwannews.com.tw, 23 Aug 2017)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralDONATIONIn 2017 she donated 1.8 million Taiwan New Dollars to Penghu Huimin Hospital in Chinese Taipei to help fund a new ambulance. "The main reason was my injury before the 2014 Asian Games. On that day the ambulance arrived really late, maybe because of a traffic jam. I couldn\'t move my leg and it really hurt. I really could feel the pain and despair of a person waiting to be rescued. It wasn\'t an open injury, with blood spewing everywhere, but you could really relate." (city543.com, 15 Sep 2017)FURTHER EDUCATIONShe has studied for a master\'s degree at Fu Jen Catholic University in Chinese Taipei. (epochtimes.com.tw, 31 Oct 2017) '), ('Influence', 'Coach Lin Jing-Neng. name: RAHI JEEVAN
bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up shooting in 2007 and began competing in 2008. (issf-sports.org, 30 May 2013)'), ('Reason', 'She was inspired to take up the sport after watching Indian shooter Tejaswini Sawant win gold at the 2006 Commonwealth Games in Melbourne, VIC, Australia. Although rifle shooting was more popular, she took up pistol purely for convenience. "Wearing the suit and setting up the equipment in rifle shooting was too cumbersome for me. So I picked up the pistol where I could shoot wearing my jeans and T-shirt." (dnaindia.com, 25 May 2011; The Hindu, 14 Oct 2008)'), ('Debut', '2008 for India (gunforglory.in, 14 Jan 2012)'), ('Coach', 'Munkhbayar Dorjsuren [personal], from 2017 (thebetterindia.com, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (rediff.com, 27 Dec 2011)'), ('Injuries', 'In 2013 she sustained an undisplaced fracture of the radial head of her elbow after falling on her right arm. bio: [('Beginning', "She took up the sport at age five in Hubei province, People's Republic of China. (gzubon.com, 12 Aug 2016)"), ('Reason', "Her parents introduced her to swimming, and she enjoyed being in the water. She played tennis in her youth and once finished runner-up in a city-level competition in People's Republic of China. However, she had to choose one sport to continue so chose swimming over tennis after finishing primary school. (gzubon.com, 12 Aug 2016; hb.xinhuanet.com, 22 Sep 2014; finance.sina.com.cn, 05 Dec 2017)"), ('Coach', 'Sen Lu [club], CHN; Haitao Liu, CHN (sports.sohu.com, 30 Jul 2017; sports.sina.com.cn, 07 Sep 2017)'), ('Awards', 'In 2015 she was named an Elite Athlete of International and National Class by the General Administration of Sport of China. (sport.gov.cn, 05 Jan 2015)'), ('Additional Information', "GeneralALMOST QUITTINGShe first joined the national team in 2006, but struggled over the next three years. In 2010 she nearly quit swimming to go to college, but after winning a minor competition and listening to advice from coaching officials in Hubei, she decided to continue swimming. She began training with the People's Liberation Army [PLA] sports team, and began to see an improvement in her results. (finance.sina.com.cn, 05 Dec 2017)FURTHER EDUCATIONShe has also studied at the China University of Geosciences in Wuhan. (Weibo profile, 23 Apr 2018) "), ('Hero', 'Korean swimmer Park Tae-hwan. name: Dutee
bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up athletics at age four in Odisha, India. (smh.com.au, 15 Jul 2016)'), ('Reason', 'She was inspired to take up athletics by her elder sister Saraswati Chand. (newindianexpress.com, 13 Jul 2016; thequint.com, 14 Jul 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Nagapuri Ramesh [national], IND (hindustantimes.com, 26 Apr 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a medal at the Olympic Games, and to compete at the 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham, England. (bbc.co.uk, 27 Apr 2018)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralHYPERANDROGENISM REGULATIONSIn 2014 she was banned for 18 months by the International Association of Athletics Federations [IAAF] after she was found to have excess levels of androgen in her body. The high levels were the result of hyperandrogenism, a condition where women have higher than average testosterone levels. She appealed the ban to the Court of Arbitration for Sport [CAS] who ruled in her favour in July 2015 and overturned the ban. In January 2018 the IAAF submitted revised hyperandrogenism regulations to CAS that were accepted, and which no longer covered events in which Chand intended to compete. "The rule is very wrong. Hyperandrogenism is natural, god-given. We were born this way, we have not done anything to our body to change it. So what can we do about it? How can we change it? The new rule is for the 400m and 800m events, and my events are 100m and 200m, so I will not be affected by the rule, but there are others like Caster Semenya who will be affected. I am very saddened by this." (thehindu.com, 17 Jul 2014; bbc.co.uk, 07 Oct 2014, 27 Apr 2018; hindustantimes.com, 26 Apr 2018; thenewsminute.com, 28 Apr 2018; tas-cas.org, 19 Jan 2018)OLYMPIC RETURNAt the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro she became the first Indian female athlete in 36 years to compete in the 100m at the Olympic Games. To commemorate the achievement Indian businessman Anand Mahindra promised to give her a car as a gift regardless of her performance after he read about the athlete\'s intention to buy a new car. (indianexpress.com, 11 Jul 2016; thequint.com, 14 Jul 2016; timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 02 Aug 2016) '), ('Influence', 'Her family and coach. (hindi.news18.com, 31 Aug 2018)'), ('Relatives', 'Her sister Saraswati Chand was a state-level runner. (thequint.com, 14 Jul 2016)'), ('Nickname', 'Nano [after the car she received as a gift for winning the school nationals] (firstpost.com, 11 Jul 2016)'), ('Injuries', 'Her training was disrupted due to a hamstring injury in April 2018. (espn.co.uk, 28 Apr 2018)She missed two weeks of training with a fractured wrist in January 2018. (indianexpress.com, 20 Jan 2018)'), ('Education', 'KIIT University, Bhubaneswar, IND'), ('Languages', 'Bengali, English, Hindi, Oriya'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationResultOlympic GamesRound 1100m2016Rio de Janeiro, BRA11.69World ChampionshipsHeats100m2017London, GBR12.07Asian Championships3100m2017Bhubaneswar, IND11.5234 x 100m Relay2017Bhubaneswar, IND44.573200m2013Pune, IND23.824200m2017Bhubaneswar, IND23.5944 x 100m Relay2015Wuhan, CHN45.72South Asian Games2200m2016India24.1424 x 100m Relay2016India45.793100m2016India11.75')]

bio: [('Beginning', "She began swimming at around age nine, when she and her family moved to Beijing, People's Republic of China. (scmp.com, 13 May 2016)'), ('Debut', '2013 for Hong Kong, China (swimswam.com, 22 Dec 2015)'), ('Awards', 'She received the Coach Wick Leadership Award while at the University of California, Berkeley in the United States of America. (calbears.com, 22 May 2016)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralFAMILY BACKGROUNDHer father is from Chinese Taipei, and her mother is from France. She was born in Hong Kong, China and attended the French International School, until her family moved to Beijing, People\'s Republic of China, when she was nine. (scmp.com, 13 May 2016; calbears.com, 22 Jan 2016)UNIVERSITY CLASSDuring her senior year at the University of California, Berkeley she led a two-credit class on female student-athlete leadership at the School of Public Health. Each Thursday she held the class, with about 30 student-athletes attending. "The first couple of weeks I wanted to get to know the class and create a safe environment for people to start talking. The goal is for the students to engage with these speakers, ask questions and gain tools that they can use with their teams and learn more about themselves as leaders." (scmp.com, 13 May 2016; calbears.com, 22 Jan 2016)LEADERSHIPShe was team captain while at the International School of Beijing between 2009 and 2011. She was also co-captain during her senior year at the University of California Berkeley. "I\'ve learned leadership. There are a million definitions for that, but I came in thinking I\'m not a leader. I can\'t be captain. I\'ve learned more about myself, what my strengths are, what my weaknesses are and how can I elevate my strengths to be a leader. I just think that everyone has something in them that they can contribute, and it\'s about bringing those traits out." (calbears.com, 22 Jan 2016; swimswam.com, 22 Dec 2015) '), ('Hero', 'US swimmer Natalie Coughlin. (hk.on.cc, 08 Jul 2016)'), ('Nickname', 'Camel (Instagram profile, 23 Jun 2016)'), ('Education', 'Psychology - University of California, Berkeley, United States'), ('Languages', 'English, French, Mandarin'), ('Highlights', "RankEventYearLocationResultAsian Games34 x 100m Freestyle Relay2014Incheon, KOR3:39.9434 x 200m Freestyle Relay2014Incheon, KOR8:04.556100m Freestyle2014Incheon, KOR56.187200m Freestyle2014Incheon, KOR2:02.06Olympic GamesHeats50m Freestyle2016Rio de Janeiro, BRA25.92Heats100m Freestyle2016Rio de Janeiro, BRA54.92Heats200m Freestyle2016Rio de Janeiro, BRA1:59.71HeatsWomen's 4 x 100m Medley Relay2016Rio de Janeiro, BRA4:03.85World ChampionshipsHeats200m Freestyle2015Kazan, RUS2:00.96Heats4 x 100m Freestyle Relay2015Kazan, RUS3:42.11Heats4 x 200m Freestyle Relay2015Kazan, RUS8:06.51HeatsWomen's 4 x 100m Medley Relay2015Kazan, RUS4:04.54")]

name: JOSHANA
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began the sport at age seven. (mapsofindia.com, 03 Feb 2014)'), ('Reason', 'Her father motivated her to take up squash. "He is my inspiration and he introduced me to the sport when I was a kid at the Madras Cricket Club. I owe taking the sport up seriously to him." (thebridge.in, 24 Mar 2018)'), ('Coach', 'Cyrus Poncha [national], IND (dnaindia.com, 17 Apr 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (zeenews.india.com, 17 Apr 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Placing first at the 2017 Asian Squash Championship in Chennai, India. (scroll.in, 01 May 2017)'), ('Awards', "In 2018 she received the Asian Squash Federation's Dato Alex Lee Award for outstanding performance in the senior women's category. (timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 20 Mar 2018)In February 2018 she was presented with the Sports Achiever Award by the Rotary Club of Madras in Chennai, India. (thehindu.com, 06 Feb 2018)In 2013 she received the Arjuna Award from the Indian government. (mid-day.com, 31 Aug 2013)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTSShe became the first Indian player to win an Asian championship title when she claimed victory at the 2017 edition of the tournament in Chennai, India. In 2014 she and Dipilka Karthik became the first Indian squash players to win gold at the Commonwealth Games when they triumphed in doubles in Glasgow, Scotland. (hindustantimes.com, 30 Apr 2017; thebridge.in, 24 Mar 2018; SportsDeskOnline, 13 Jun 2018)CAREER CHANGING INJURYThe knee injury she suffered in 2011 changed her outlook on the sport. "I feel the knee surgery was the best thing that could have happened to me. It changed everything about my life, whether it was the company I kept or the way I approached my game. It was like starting my career from scratch after being on the couch for six months". (asianage.com, 28 Apr 2014) '), ('Hero', 'US basketball player Michael Jordan, Indian sprinter PT Usha. (wispa.net, 07 Jun 2007; sports.indiainfo.com, 22 Nov 2009)'), ('Relatives', 'Her family has been playing squash for the previous four generations. Her great-grandfather Field Marshall KM Cariappa, who was also the first Commander-in-Chief of the Indian Army, was a regular player of squash, and her father Anjan Chinappa also played squash regularly and represented Tamil Nadu several times. (mapsofindia.com, 03 Feb 2014)'), ('Injuries', 'She suffered a serious knee injury in 2011 that required surgery. The injury kept her out of action for six months. (asianage.com, 28 Apr 2014)'), ('Education', 'English - Ethiraj College, India'), ('Languages', 'English, Hindi'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationAsian Games2Team2014Incheon, KOR3Team2010Guangzhou, CHN5Singles2014Incheon, KOR5Singles2010Guangzhou, CHN5Singles2006Doha, QAT5Singles2002Busan, KORWorld Games9Singles2013Cali, COLWorld Championships5Singles2016El Gouna, EGY9Singles2015Kuala Lumpur, MAS9Singles2014Cairo, EGY17Singles2017Manchester, GBR17Singles2013George Town, MAS17Singles2009Amsterdam, NEDWorld Team Championships5Team2012Nimes, FRA9Team2016Paris, FRA14Team2014Niagara-on-the-Lake, ON, CANWorld Doubles Championships3Doubles W2017Wroclaw, POL3Doubles W2016Darwin, NT, AUS3Doubles X2016Darwin, NT, AUS7Doubles X2017Wroclaw, POL7Doubles X2004Chennai, INDAsian Individual Championships1Singles2017Chennai, IND2Team2010Chennai, IND3Singles2015Kuwait City, KUW3Singles2008KuwaitSouth Asian Games1Singles2016Guwahati, IND1Team2016Guwahati, IND1Singles2006Colombo, SRI1Singles2004Islamabad, PAKCommonwealth Games1Doubles W2014Glasgow, GBR2Doubles W2018Gold Coast, QLD, AUS5Singles2018Gold Coast, QLD, AUS5Doubles X2018Gold Coast, QLD, AUSWorld Ranking (as of 01 Aug 2018)16Singles2018')]

name: DIPIKA PALLIKAL
bio: [('Beginning', "She took up squash at age 10 and played her first Women's Squash Association [WSA] game at age 15. (mumbaimirror.com, 03 Feb 2014; worldsquash.org, 02 Sep 2014)"), ('Coach', 'Sarah Fitz-Gerald [personal], AUS (eenaduindia.com, 10 Apr 2018)'), ('Awards', "In 2014 she was given the Vocational Excellence Award by the Rotary Club of Madras, India. (fairandglow.com, 12 Mar 2014)In 2014 she became the youngest recipient of the Padma Shri Award, given out by the Indian government to recognise contributions in areas such as sport. (actsfaqs.com, 29 Jan 2014)She received the Ethiraj College Alumni award for her achievements in squash in 2013. (fairandglow.com, 12 Mar 2014)In 2012 she was given the Arjuna Award by the Indian government for sporting excellence. She was the first squash player to receive it. (fairandglow.com, 12 Mar 2014)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTShe became the first Indian female squash player to win an individual medal at the Asian Games when she won bronze in singles at the 2014 Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea. (sports.ndtv.com, 22 Sep 2014; SportsDeskOnline, 01 Jul 2018) '), ('Influence', 'Her family. (idiva.com, 13 May 2013)'), ('Relatives', 'Her husband Dinesh Karthik has represented India in cricket, and captained Indian club side Kolkata Knightriders during the 2018 edition of the Indian Premier League. bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up paragliding in 2006 in Malang, Indonesia. (asumsi.co, 31 Jul 2018)'), ('Reason', 'She was encouraged by her father to take up paragliding. "I never had the thought of becoming an athlete, especially paragliding. I was afraid of heights. But my father was very persuasive and I was just going with it. And I remember I was unable to open my eyes in my first tandem training. I was very scared." (asumsi.co, 31 Jul 2018)RETIREMENT PLANSShe has contemplated retiring after the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. "I am no longer the world champion. I can see much younger and more talented paragliders in the national team. So I think it is time for me to retire after the Asian Games." name: ERI
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began cycling in 2012 when she was a university student. (sankei.com, 15 Sep 2017)'), ('Reason', 'She initially joined the tennis club at university, but she was not very good at the sport. Her uncle then suggested she should try cycling and bought her a bike. (cyclowired.jp, 18 Dec 2013)'), ('Debut', 'Turned professional in 2016'), ('Coach', 'Allan Davis [club], AUS (wigglehighfive.com, 08 Aug 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (cyclingnews.com, 29 Jun 2016)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralROCKY ROAD TO RIOIn April 2016 she was removed from the long list of athletes eligible to compete at the Olympic Games by the Japanese Cycling Federation after she failed to follow team orders to ride for her more experienced teammate Mayuko Hagiwara at the 2016 Asian Championships in Oshima, Japan. She appealed to the Japan Sports Arbitration Agency [JSAA], which ruled in her favour the day before the road race at the 2016 Japanese Championships. She went on to win the time trial, and then beat Hagiwara into second place on the final lap of the road race to secure her place for the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. "At the beginning of this season while I was discussing my goals with my coach, we both agreed that Rio should be our number one priority. It has been a huge challenge for both of us. I have worked so hard, and I have learned so much from everyone around me. I always respect my competitors, and I appreciate everyone who made this journey possible." (cyclingnews.com, 29 Jun 2016) '), ('Relatives', 'To win a medal in the individual time trial at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (cyclist.sanspo.com, 15 Aug 2016)'), ('Education', 'School of Health and Physical Education University of Tsukuba, Japan'), ('Languages', 'English, Japanese'), ('Hobbies', 'Playing tennis. bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up hockey after moving to Kairon, India. In 2006 she started basic training with coach Sharanjeet Singh from Punjab Police in Kairon, India. (tribuneindia.com, 12 Nov 2017; tribuneindia.com, 06 Nov 2017)'), ('Debut', '2014 for India against Malaysia (Athlete, 17 Aug 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a gold medal at the Olympic Games, and to become the best drag flicker in the world.. (jagbani.punjabkesari.in, 08 Nov 2017; Athlete, 17 Aug 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning the 2017 Asia Cup. (Athlete, 17 Aug 2018)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralDEVELOPMENTShe was India\'s top scorer at the 2017 Asia Cup in Kakamigahara, Japan, finishing the competition with eight goals. She put her success down to changes she made to her drag-flicking technique after working with Dutch coach Toon Siepman ahead of the tournament. "With Siepman, I corrected the basics like keeping my head up, how to turn my body and the stepping during the drag-flicking process. These were minor changes, but I had never realised earlier that I was doing it incorrectly. He told me, \'Just make these small changes and you can become the best drag-flicker in the world\'. I keep that in mind every time I work on drag-flicking." (tribuneindia.com, 12 Nov 2017) '), ('Hero', 'Her father. (Athlete, 17 Aug 2018)'), ('Influence', 'Her father. [('Beginning', 'She began playing hockey in 2001 at the Shahbad Hockey Academy in India. (Athlete, 17 Aug 2018)'), ('Debut', '2008 for India, Olympic Qualification Tournament in Russian Federation (Athlete, 17 Aug 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a medal at the World Cup or Olympic Games. (Athlete, 17 Aug 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Competing at the 2010 World Cup in Rosario, Argentina. (Athlete, 17 Aug 2018)'), ('Awards', "She received Hockey India's Forward of the Year award for 2015. (sportskeeda.com, 26 Mar 2016)She was named Player of the Tournament at the 2013 Junior World Cup in Monchengladbach, Germany, and Best Young Player at the 2010 World Cup in Rosario, Argentina. (gosportsfoundation.in, 05 Aug 2010; hockeyindia.org, 05 Aug 2013)She was included in the International Hockey Federation [FIH] All-Star team in 2010, and nominated for the FIH Young Player of the Year award in 2010, 2013 and 2014. (indianexpress.com, 19 Jul 2015. fih.ch, 06 May 2016)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralEARLY DAYSShe comes from a poor background in Shahabad, Haryana, where her father worked as a cart-puller, transporting goods by hand. When she was growing up she had to decide on following her passion for hockey or taking responsibility for her family. She chose to do both, although it was not a universally popular decision. "In my neighbourhood, people asked my parents to not let me wear shorts and play hockey. They felt I might bring a bad name to the family." She asked her parents for one chance to prove herself, and they managed to enrol her at the Shahabad Hockey Academy. When she first entered the academy at age seven, coach Baldev Singh rejected her, saying she was too frail, but she did not give up and returned the following day. The coach ignored the academy\'s rule not to admit any girl under the age of eight and allowed her to train. "She was so gifted that I had to relax the rule for her, and I am glad I did," Singh said. She eventually made her senior debut for India at age 14 and went on to become part of the team that won bronze at the 2013 Junior World Cup in Monchengladbach, Germany. (sportskeeda.com, 16 Apr 2015; indianexpress.com, 19 Jul 2015; fih.ch, 06 Nov 2015) '), ('Influence', 'Coach Baldev Singh. (Athlete, 17 Aug 2018)'), ('Nickname', 'Rano (Athlete, 17 Aug 2018)'), ('Injuries', "In April 2016 she injured her ankle in a match against Ireland at the Hawke's Bay Cup in New Zealand. (newindianexpress.com, 10 Apr 2016)She missed nine months with a dislocated shoulder and a back injury, before returning to action in June 2015. (sportskeeda.com, 16 Apr 2015; zeenews.india.com, 24 Jun 2015; Athlete, 17 Aug 2018)"), ('Education', 'Kurukshetra University, India'), ('Languages', 'English, Hindi, Punjabi'), ('Hobbies', 'Listening to music, shopping, going to the gym. (Athlete, 17 Aug 2018)'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationAsian Games3Women2014Incheon, KOR4Women2010Guangzhou, CHNOlympic Games12Women2016Rio de Janeiro, BRAWorld Cup8Women2018London, GBR9Women2010Rosario, ARGAsia Cup1Women2017Kakamigahara, JPN2Women2009Bangkok, THA3Women2013Kuala Lumpur, MAS')]

name: JYOTHI SUREKHA
bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up archery in 2007. (newindianexpress.com, 27 Sep 2014)'), ('Reason', 'She initially competed in swimming but switched to archery due to a lack of international swimming coaches in her city. "I would have had to go to Bengaluru. I was quite young then and my parents didn\'t want to send me so far away. After some research, we settled on archery. I loved being in the water and initially, I didn\'t want to do archery. But as I got better at the sport, I knew this was for me." name: V. SINDHU
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began playing badminton at age eight. She initially trained at the Indian Railway Institute of Signal Engineering and Telecommunications in Secunderabad, India, before joining Gopichand Academy in Hyderabad in 2008. (firstpost.com, 26 Feb 2018; ONS, 20 Jul 2016)'), ('Reason', '"My dad used to play volleyball and I would accompany him to the volleyball courts when I was very young. There was a badminton court beside the volleyball courts and I initially only played for fun, but I gradually developed a great interest and love for badminton." (rediff.com, 03 Jan 2012)'), ('Debut', '2010 for India (hindustantimes.com, 29 Aug 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Pullela Gopichand [national], IND (timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 08 Mar 2018, 21 Feb 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a gold medal at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 20 Feb 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning silver in the singles event at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (bwfbadminton.com, 19 Aug 2016)'), ('Awards', 'She was flag bearer for India at the opening ceremony of the 2018 Commonwealth Games in Gold Coast, QLD, Australia. (gc2018.com, 04 Apr 2018)In August 2016 she received the Rajiv Gandhi Khel Ratna Award, the highest sporting honour in India. (thehindu.com, 29 Aug 2016)In 2015 she was presented with a Padma Shri, the fourth-highest civilian award given by the Indian government. (sports.ndtv.com, 30 Mar 2015)She was named the 2014 Breakthrough Sportsperson of the Year by the Federation of Indian Chambers of Commerce and Industry [FICCI]. (news.biharprabha.com, 13 Feb 2014)She was named the 2013 CNN-IBN Indian of the Year in the sports category. (sportskeeda.com, 20 Dec 2013)In 2013 she received the Arjuna Award in recognition of her outstanding achievements in badminton. (ONS, 20 Jul 2016; daijiworld.com, 25 Sep 2013)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTSIn 2016 she became the first athlete representing India to win a silver medal in badminton at the Olympic Games by finishing runner-up in the singles event in Rio de Janeiro. In 2013 she became the first Indian female to claim a medal in the singles event at the world championships when she took bronze in Guangzhou, People\'s Republic of China. (SportsDeskOnline, 19 Aug 2016; ONS, 20 Jul 2016; olympicgoldquest.in, 18 Jan 2015)GIFT FROM HER HEROShe received the gift of a new car from Indian cricketer Sachin Tendulkar as a reward for winning a gold medal at the 2012 Asian Junior Championships in Gimcheon, Republic of Korea. "The car is very special to me. To be given a gift by Sachin was like living a dream." (telegraphindia.com, 23 Mar 2014) '), ('Hero', 'Indian badminton players Pullela Gopichand and Saina Nehwal, Indian cricketer Sachin Tendulkar. (telegraphindia.com, 23 Mar 2014; sportskeeda.com, 14 May 2013; rediff.com, 03 Jan 2012)'), ('Influence', 'Her parents, and coach Pullela Gopichand. (telegraphindia.com, 23 Mar 2014; sportskeeda.com, 14 May 2013)'), ('Relatives', 'Her father PV Ramana won a bronze medal in volleyball at the 1986 Asian Games in Seoul, Republic of Korea. Her mother P Vijaya was a professional volleyball player. (hindustantimes.com, 29 Aug 2016; ONS, 20 Jul 2016; olympicgoldquest.in, 18 Jan 2015)'), ('Injuries', "She sprained her right ankle ahead of the 2018 Commonwealth Games in Gold Coast, QLD, Australia, but was still able to compete at the event. She first noticed the pain in 2014, but she thought it was just stiffness and decided to continue playing. name: LUKSIKA
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began playing tennis at age three in Chanthaburi, Thailand. (Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Reason', 'Her father was a coach. (Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Coach', 'Aktitthep Kulikul [national]; Subin Sricha-aen [personal] (thairath.co.th, 20 Jul 2018; nationmultimedia.com, 01 Apr 2018; Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2020 Olympic Games in Toyko. (posttoday.com, 21 Jan 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Reaching the third round of the 2018 Australian Open in Melbourne, VIC, Australia. (news18.com, 17 Jan 2018)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralTIGHT BUDGETIn 2018 she opted to enter smaller tournaments in Asia rather than going to the hard-court season in the United States of America because she couldn\'t afford to travel with her coach. "With the budget I have, I can only take my coach to some tournaments. That\'s why I haven\'t gone to the US because I couldn\'t compete without a mentor or someone I can consult with in a place far away like that. Even junior players have to travel with their coaches." (nationmultimedia.com, 01 Apr 2018)INCREASING INTERESTIn 2018 she managed to reach the third round of the Australian Open for the first time in her career. She said she hoped her performance would help increase interest in tennis in Thailand. "My dad is a tennis coach and when Paradorn Srichaphan was doing well [in the 2000s], he [her father] always had a lot of young players wanting to learn." (tnp.sg, 17 Jan 2018) '), ('Hero', 'US tennis player Monica Seles, Thai tennis player Tamarine Tanasugarn. (wtatennis.com, 28 Jul 2014; Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Influence', 'Her father. name: RU EN ROANNE
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began swimming at age eight. (Athlete, 02 Dec 2006)'), ('Reason', 'Her father signed her and her sister up for water safety classes. (myactivesg.com, 19 Jul 2017)'), ('Coach', 'Gary Tan [national] (tnp.sg, 04 Apr 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning a bronze medal at the 2004 Commonwealth Youth Games in Bendigo, VIC, Australia. (swimming.org.sg, 2017)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralANXIETYAt the conclusion of her events at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia she revealed that she had been struggling with anxiety. "My pain was not poetic, it was days without sleep and pretending I was stable enough to continue. I was so crippled by anxiety, and the fear of being a failure or a disappointment." She revealed it was the outcome of the competition that most affected her. "Sport is so heavily results driven, there will always be a bigger competition or a faster time. That\'s when it hit me, if I felt like I wasn\'t enough without a medal, I would never be enough even with a medal, if I were to base my self worth on my results, I would never be okay with who I am." (asiaone.com, 26 Aug 2018)ROLE MODELShe was determined to return to competitive action and support younger swimmers after suffering a collapsed lung and a shoulder injury in 2016. "When I read stories about people who are injured, most of them either quit or just can\'t get back to where they once were. Every day was a struggle. When I was going through that, I kept thinking if so many people have failed, what makes me think that I can do it? There\'s a younger generation and most of them will get injuries and get their preparations affected, so that\'s my driving purpose right now, to prove that they can still come out on top of whatever happens." (tnp.sg, 04 Apr 2018) '), ('Relatives', 'Her older sister Ruth has also represented Singapore in swimming. (ssc.gov.sg, 23 Feb 2007)'), ('Nickname', 'Ro (Athlete, 02 Dec 2006)'), ('Injuries', 'In April 2016 she suffered a shoulder injury. She underwent surgery in June 2016 and returned to training six weeks later. (straitstimes.com, 03 Sep 2017)In January 2016 she suffered a collapsed lung that kept her from training for a month after surgery. (straitstimes.com, 03 Sep 2017)'), ('Education', 'Marketing - Queensland University of Technology, Brisbane, QLD, AUS'), ('Languages', 'English, Mandarin'), ('Hobbies', 'Watching films and television. name: Oksana
bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up gymnastics at age seven. (Asiad Daily, 26 Sep 2014)'), ('Debut', '1987 for Soviet Union (sportcentric.com, 06 Oct 2013)'), ('Coach', 'Svetlana Boguinskaia [personal], BLR (gazeta.uz, 07 Feb 2018)'), ('Training', 'She trains for 15 to 20 hours a week. (fig-gymnastics.com, 01 Jun 2017)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (fig-gymnastics.com, 01 Jun 2017)'), ('Awards', 'She was inducted into the International Gymnastics Hall of Fame in May 2017. (intlgymnast.com, 21 May 2017)She holds the title of Honoured Master of Sport in Uzbekistan. (anons.uz, 03 Dec 2013)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralOLYMPIC FIRSTShe became the first gymnast to compete at seven Olympic Games when she competed at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. In 2017 she also announced that she would try to qualify for her eighth Olympic Games, in 2020 in Tokyo. "I am taking it step by step to see how far physically my body will take me. Of course I want to do more, otherwise I would not be training." (fig-gymnastics.com, 01 Jun 2017; intlgymnast.com, 21 May 2017; SportsDeskOnline, 29 Jul 2018)CAREERBorn in Bukhara, Uzbekistan, she made her international debut for the Soviet Union. Following the dissolution of the Soviet Union, she represented the Commonwealth of Independent States [CIS] at the 1992 Olympic Games in Barcelona and later began competing for Uzbekistan. In 2002 her son Alisher was diagnosed with leukaemia, so her family moved to Germany where he could receive treatment. She obtained German citizenship in 2006, winning a silver medal for her adopted nation at the 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing. She returned to compete for Uzbekistan in 2013, having been given special dispensation by the executive committee of the International Gymnastics Federation [FIG]. (uznews.net, 06 Mar 2013; heraldscotland.com, 16 Oct 2015)FROM TEAMMATE TO COACHShe and her coach, Svetlana Boguinskaya, were members of the gold medal-winning Unified team at the 1992 Olympic Games in Barcelona, Spain. (sports-reference.com, 28 Jul 1992)ATHLETE REPRESENTATIVEIn October 2017 she was elected the women\'s artistic gymnastics representative for the International Gymnastics Federation [FIG] Athletes Commission. (gymnovosti.com, 06 Oct 2017) '), ('Relatives', 'Her husband Bakhodir Kurbanov represented Uzbekistan in wrestling at the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney. (sports-reference.com, 12 Aug 2012)'), ('Injuries', 'She was suffering with a foot and ankle injury at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea, so decided to not compete in the all-around and instead compete on vault. (insidethgames.biz, 24 Sep 2014; ndtv.com, 25 Sep 2014)She had an operation on her shoulder in 2008 and required back surgery in January 2009. (gymmedia.de, 17 Jan 2009)She tore her Achilles tendon at the 2008 Swiss Cup in Zurich, Switzerland. (intlgymnast.com, 02 Nov 2008)She sustained a leg injury ahead of the 2004 Olympic Games in Athens, which meant she was only able to compete on vault. name: Shervegar
bio: [('Coach', 'Pete Conway [personal], GBR (thebridge.in, 06 Jul 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 06 Aug 2018)'), ('Additional Information', "Main classes currently sailed49er FX (timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 06 Aug 2018)GeneralSELECTION APPEALIn July 2018 she and partner Varsha Gautham appealed to the Delhi High Court to challenge the decision of the Yachting Association of India [YAI] to not select the pair for the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. The court ruled that YAI should hold an additional selection trial in Jakarta to confirm the team, but as the sailing venue was no longer available, the court then ruled that Gautham and Shervegar should be selected to compete at the Games. The Indian Olympic Association [IOA] complied with the court's decision and the pair were included in the Indian team to compete in Indonesia. They eventually won a silver medal in the 49erFX event. (newindianexpress.com, 04 Aug 2018; thehindu.com, 06 Aug 2018; sportstarlive.com, 07 Aug 2018; firstpost.com, 31 Aug 2018) "), ('Education', 'Medicine - YMT Medical College, Mumbai, IND'), ('Languages', 'English, Hindi'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationClass World Championships5649er FX2017Porto, PORAsian Championships249er FX2018Jakarta, INA')]

name: Gautham
bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up the sport at age eight. (thenewsminute.com, 03 Jul 2018)'), ('Reason', 'She loved swimming, which led to her trying her hand at sailing. "Since I started sailing, it has been one of the most important parts of my life." (asianage.com, 23 Mar 2014)'), ('Coach', 'Pete Conway [personal], GBR (thebridge.in, 06 Jul 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a medal at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (sportstarlive.com, 07 Aug 2018)'), ('Additional Information', 'Main classes currently sailed49er (newindianexpress.com, 04 Aug 2018)GeneralSELECTION APPEALIn July 2018 she and partner Shaila Shervegar appealed to the Delhi High Court to challenge the decision of the Yachting Association of India [YAI] to not select the pair for the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. The court ruled that YAI should hold an additional selection trial in Jakarta to confirm the team, but as the sailing venue was no longer available, the court then ruled that Gautham and Shervegar should be selected to compete at the Games. The Indian Olympic Association [IOA] complied with the court\'s decision and the pair were included in the Indian team to compete in Indonesia. They eventually won a silver medal in the 49erFX event. "These were stressful three months. But everything has paid off. At least 10 times I thought, \'it\'s not worth it, I can\'t handle it,\' but somehow I continued." (newindianexpress.com, 04 Aug 2018; thehindu.com, 06 Aug 2018; sportstarlive.com, 07 Aug 2018; firstpost.com, 31 Aug 2018)YOUNGESTShe became the youngest Indian sailor to win a medal at the Asian Games when she won bronze in the women\'s 29er event at the 2014 edition in Incheon, Republic of Korea. (thebridge.in, 06 Jul 2018; edexlive.com, 29 Jun 2017; SportsDeskOnline, 17 Aug 2018) '), ('Injuries', 'In 2014 she broke two bones in her left foot. She was back on the water within two weeks with her cast waterproofed. In May 2014, during her first Olympic class event in Lake Garda, Italy, she injured her foot once again and could not compete after the first day. (theweekendleader.com, 06 Jun 2014)'), ('Education', 'Sociology - MOP Vaishnav College for Women, Chennai, IND'), ('Languages', 'English, Hindi, Malayalam, Tamil'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationAsian Games329er2014Incheon, KORISAF World Championships5349er FX2014Santander, ESPClass World Championships4349er FX2015Buenos Aires, ARG5649er FX2017Porto, PORWorld Cup3449er FX2016Miami, FL, USA4049er FX2015Miami, FL, USAAsian Championships249er FX2018Jakarta, INA649er FX2016Abu Dhabi, UAEClass World Championships Juniors2149er FX2015Flensburg, GERWorld Ranking (as of 11 Jun 2018)6649er FX Individual Ranking2018')]

name: GREYSIA
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began playing badminton at age five in Manado, Indonesia. At age eight she decided that she wanted to pursue the sport seriously, so her family moved to Jakarta to support her training. She joined the national training setup in 2003. (manadopostonline.com, 28 Dec 2017; olahraga.kompas.com, 31 Oct 2014)'), ('Reason', 'She was inspired by Indonesian players Ricky Subagja and Rexy Mainaky. "Every time I watched Ricky and Rexy on television, I always imagined how would it be like to travel around the world by playing badminton. I was lucky that we had a small badminton field in the area. I always went there to play after watching those badminton stars on television." (olahraga.kompas.com, 31 Oct 2014)'), ('Coach', 'Eng Hian [national], INA (juara.bolasport.com, 08 Mar 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia, and win an Olympic or world championship gold medal. (cnnindonesia.com, 02 Jul 2016; jawapos.com, 07 Jun 2018)'), ('Memorable', "Winning gold in the women's doubles at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea, which was the first Indonesian women's doubles gold medal at an Asian Games since 1978. (badzine.net, 28 Sep 2014; kumparan.com, 17 Mar 2018; SportsDeskOnline, 12 Jun 2018)"), ('Additional Information', "GeneralLONGEST MATCHShe and her former partner Nitya Krishinda Maheswari set a record for the longest international women's doubles match while playing Japanese pair Kurumi Yonao and Naoko Fukuman in the semifinal of the 2016 Asian Championships in Wuhan, People's Republic of China. Polii and Mahessawari eventually lost the 161-minute long match 13-21, 21-19, 24-22. (bwfbadminton.com, 30 Apr 2016)OLYMPIC DISQUALIFICATIONShe and former partner Meiliana Jauhari were disqualified from the women's doubles competition at the 2012 Olympic Games in London, after a Badminton World Federation [BWF] disciplinary committee ruled they had deliberately attempted to lose a group match in order to manipulate the draw for the knockout stage. The pair were charged by the BWF with 'not using one's best efforts to win a match', and 'conducting oneself in a manner that is abusive or detrimental to the sport'. In addition, both players were suspended for four months by the Badminton Association of Indonesia. The BWF also disqualified three other pairs for committing the same offences during the women's doubles tournament at the Games. (bbc.co.uk, 01 Aug 2012) "), ('Hero', 'Indonesian badminton players Ricky Subagja and Rexy Mainaky. (olahraga.kompas.com, 31 Oct 2014)'), ('Influence', 'Her mother Evie Pakasi. name: MAN WAI VIVIAN
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began fencing in 2005 at age 11. (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016; fie.org, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Reason', 'She tried a number of sports, including dancing and taekwondo, before finding fencing. "I was interested in taekwondo and so I did it all the way until I was age 11 and I got my black belt. But then my mother still wanted me to dance and in between she made me do ice skating. I liked it, but I was not so good at it. And then my father stepped in and said, \'Why don\'t you try fencing?\' Fencing is like the ballet of sports, it is very elegant. I really, really liked fencing so I started it at age 11." (fie.org, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Debut', '2008 for Hong Kong, China, World Cup in Nanjing, China (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Octavian Zidaru, ROU (scmp.com, 29 Aug 2018)'), ('Training', 'She trains up to five hours a day. She combines her fencing training with yoga and cross-training. (scmp.com, 29 Aug 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (scmp.com, 29 Aug 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Competing at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (hk.on.cc, 07 Aug 2016)'), ('Awards', "She was named Hong Kong, China's flag bearer for the opening ceremony of the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (AG Entries, 18 Aug 2018)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTShe became the first female fencer from Hong Kong, China to win a gold medal at the Asian Championships, when she was victorious in the individual epee at the 2018 edition of the tournament in Bangkok, Thailand. (scmp.com, 20 Jun 2018; SportsDeskOnline, 21 Jun 2018) '), ('Hero', 'Romanian fencer Ana Maria Popescu. name: Chitra
bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up athletics in grade seven of school in Kerala, India. (thenewsminute.com, 25 Jul 2017)'), ('Reason', 'Her physical education teacher at school Sjin NS recognised her potential and encouraged her to take up athletics. "When I was in class seven I was intrigued by the senior girls taking part in sports events, and decided to take part in school competitions myself. It was some two years later that I began to win medals. Since class nine I don\'t remember winning anything less than a gold medal." (yourstory.com, 17 Jul 2017; herstoryapp.com, 12 Mar 2018; thenewsminute.com, 25 Jul 2017)'), ('Coach', 'Nikolai Snesarev [national], BLR; Sjin NS [personal], IND (sportstarlive.com, 12 Dec 2017; timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 10 Jul 2017)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralWORLD CHAMPIONSHIPS EXCLUSIONShe filed a complaint to the High Court of Kerala in India after she was not included in the Indian squad for the 2017 World Championships in London, England. The High Court of Kerala ruled in her favour and directed the Athletics Federation of India [AFI] to include her in the squad for the championships. However, the AFI\'s application to include her in the squad was rejected by the International Association of Athletics Federations [IAAF] as the deadline for squad submissions has passed. "I had performed my level best at the [2017] Asian Championships and had won the gold medal, despite the unfavourable weather conditions during the race. And I was told my gold medal would be my direct ticket to the World Championships in London. When my coach Sijin informed me that my name was not on the list of participants, I was devastated." (herstoryapp.com, 12 Mar 2018; outlookindia.com, 20 Sep 2017; newindianexpress.com, 30 Jul 2017; thenewsminute.com, 25 Jul 2017; timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 30 Jul 2017) '), ('Influence', 'Her coach Sjin NS. (timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 10 Jul 2017)'), ('Education', 'VTB College, Palakkad, IND'), ('Languages', 'English, Hindi, Malayalam'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationResultAsian Championships11500m2017Bhubaneswar, IND4:17.92South Asian Games11500m2016India4:25.59')]

(ezinearticles.com, 27 Jun 2010)'), ('Reason', 'Her parents were both badminton players. (olympicgoldquest.in, 16 Aug 2015)'), ('Coach', 'Pullela Gopichand [club, national], IND (sportskeeda.com, 10 Mar 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a medal at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 05 Nov 2017)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning gold at the 2010 Commonwealth Games in Delhi, India. (olympicgoldquest.in, 16 Aug 2015)'), ('Awards', "In 2016 she received the Padma Bhushan, the third-highest civilian award given by the Indian government. (ONS, 20 Jul 2016)She was named Sports Illustrated India's Sportsperson of the Year in 2009 and 2013. (zeenews.india.com, 01 Oct 2013)In 2010 she received a Padma Shri, the fourth-highest civilian award given by the Indian government. (olympicgoldquest.in, 29 Aug 2013)In 2010 she received the Rajiv Gandhi Khel Ratna [RGKR], India's highest honour for achievements in sport. (olympicgoldquest.in, 29 Aug 2013)In 2009 she received an Arjuna Award in recognition of her outstanding achievements in badminton. (olympicgoldquest.in, 29 Aug 2013)She was named 2009 CNN-IBN Indian of the Year in the sports category. (sportskeeda.com, 20 Dec 2013)She was named 2008 Most Promising Player of the Year by the Badminton World Federation [BWF]. (ONS, 20 Jul 2016)"), ('Additional Information', "GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTSShe became the first Indian badminton player to win gold at the world junior championships when she was triumphant in singles at the 2008 edition of the tournament in Pune, India. In 2009 she became the first Indian badminton player to win a Badminton World Federation [BWF] Super Series title when she claimed victory in singles at the Indonesian Open in Jakarta. In 2010 she also became the first Indian female athlete to win an individual gold medal in badminton at the Commonwealth Games when she was victorious in singles at the Games in Delhi, India. At the 2012 Olympic Games in London, she claimed India's first Olympic medal in badminton by winning bronze in singles. She is also the first Indian badminton player to have competed at three Olympic Games, having participated at the 2008, 2012 and 2016 editions of the Games. (SportsDeskOnline, 31 Jul 2018; ONS, 20 Jul 2016; olympicgoldquest.in, 16 Aug 2015)AUTOBIOGRAPHYIn 2012 she published an autobiography titled 'Playing To Win, My Life On And Off Court'. (ibnlive.in.com, 08 Nov 2012) "), ('Hero', 'Indian badminton players Aparna Popat and Pullela Gopichand, Swiss tennis player Roger Federer, Indian cricketer Sachin Tendulkar. (olympicgoldquest.in, 16 Aug 2015; rediff.com, 07 Jun 2013; tssonnet.com, 14 Sep 2007)'), ('Relatives', 'Her parents were both district badminton champions in Haryana, India. (olympicgoldquest.in, 16 Aug 2015; ONS, 20 Jul 2016)'), ('Injuries', 'She underwent surgery on a knee injury in August 2017. (timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 05 Nov 2017)A groin injury ruled her out of the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, Scotland. (hindustantimes.com, 5 Nov 2016)In 2013 she suffered various minor injuries, including a fractured toe and an injured ankle. (mid-day.com, 24 Dec 2013)In 2012 she was troubled by a persistent right-knee injury. name: SAMANTHA LOUISA GINN
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began swimming at age five. (teamsingapore.com.sg, 08 Nov 2011)'), ('Reason', '"I remember winning my first ever medal, a silver, at a group meet for the 21m backstroke and that is the exact moment I fell in love with the sport." (Team Media Guide, 28 Jul 2014)'), ('Coach', 'Stephan Widmer [national], AUS; Gary Tan [national], SGP (swimming.org.sg, 14 Jun 2018; swimmingworldmagazine.com, 18 Jul 2018)'), ('Awards', 'She received a Team Meritorious award at the 2012 Singapore Sports Awards. (singaporeolympics.com, 2013)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralWOLVERINEShe competed for the University of Michigan Wolverines from 2014 to 2018. She raced her last race for the Wolverines in March 2018 and enjoyed her time there. "I could not be more proud to be surrounded by such a grounded, determined, and inspiring group of individuals. It has truly been an honour to fight for the Block M [University of Michigan]. And while I have fallen short of some of my goals as my four years officially comes to a close, you all have made it so, so special. From our worst practises to our best races and everything in between, this team has showered me with countless memories that have strengthened me and will be with me for the rest of my life." (mgoblue.com, 01 Apr 2018; Instagram profile, 18 Mar 2018) '), ('Injuries', 'In October 2013 she dislocated her right knee after slipping during dry land training. She recovered in time to compete at the 2013 South East Asian Games in Naypyidaw, Myanmar. (Facebook page, 10 May 2015)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTSHer appearance at the 2012 Olympic Games in London made her the first female Malaysian athlete to have competed at four editions of the Games. The pair claimed bronze in the 3m synchronised springboard in Busan, Republic of Korea. Then in 2009, she and her partner Pandelela Rinong became the first divers representing Malaysia to win a medal at the world championships, claiming bronze in the 10m synchronised platform event in Rome, Italy. name: AMITA MARIE NICOLETTE
bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up the sport at the Z Fencing Academy in Novena, Singapore. (straitstimes.com, 03 Sep 2017)'), ('Reason', "Her father originally enrolled her and her sister Aarya in the Junior Soccer School and League [JSSL] football academy in Singapore. However, Amita's school did not have football as a curricular activity, so she switched to fencing. (straitstimes.com, 03 Sep 2017)"), ('Coach', 'Andrey Klyushin [national], RUS; Ralf Bissdorf [personal] (straitstimes.com, 17 Dec 2017; straitstimes.com, 10 Apr 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (straitstimes.com, 17 Dec 2017)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralLIVING IN THE USAIn January 2017 she ended her studies in Singapore and moved to the United States of America, where she began training at the Marx Fencing Academy in Concord, Massachusetts. She plans to begin studying at the University of Notre Dame in Indiana, in September 2018, and compete for the university\'s fencing team. "I knew if I wanted to win medals something had to give, and in my case it was school. After a month break at the end of 2017, I visited family in Europe to recharge after a long year and it was then I received the offer from Notre Dame." (Facebook profile, Dec 2017; straitstimes.com, 03 Sep 2017, 13 Jan 2018) '), ('Influence', 'Her father, and coach Ralf Bissdorf. name: WEE WERN
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began playing at age nine, and professionally at age 17. Her first coach when she took up squash was Lianne David, the sister of fellow Malaysian squash player Nicol David. "She was my first coach at age 10 when I was representing Penang at state level and Malaysia as a junior. Then I moved on to work with coach Aaron Soyza when I was 12." (nst.com.my, 18 Dec 2017; fourthofficial.com, 13 Feb 2017)'), ('Reason', 'She began squash lessons when her mother gave her a choice between squash and tennis. "I had two options, tennis or squash, and well, being a Malaysian, tennis wasn\'t the best option because of the weather, so I picked squash. But to be honest, I had no clue what it was." (fourthofficial.com, 13 Feb 2017)'), ('Coach', 'Peter Genever [national], GBR; Aaron Soyza [personal] (thestar.com.my, 01 Apr 2018; nst.com.my, 18 Dec 2017)'), ('Ambition', "To reach the top 10 rankings in singles again on the Professional Squash Association [PSA] World Tour, and to win a gold medal in the women's team event at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (nst.com.my, 18 Dec 2017)"), ('Awards', "In 2006 and 2008 she received the Hassan Musa Award for the Most Outstanding Junior Women's Performance from the Asian Squash Federation. (WISPA, 05 Aug 2010)"), ('Hero', 'Malaysian squash player Nicol David. (tocsquash.com, 22 Jan 2014)'), ('Influence', 'Her mother, and coach Aaron Soyza. (fourthofficial.com, 13 Feb 2017)'), ('Injuries', 'In March 2015 she suffered an anterior cruciate ligament [ACL] injury to her left knee which required surgery, and initially returned to competition in November 2015. By late 2016 a scan revealed that the initial graph in place on her ligament had disappeared, which meant she missed the whole of 2017 as she required another bout of surgery to reconstruct the ligament. She hoped to return for the 2018 Commonwealth Games in Gold Coast, QLD, Australia, but was unable to recover in time. She finally returned to competition after a 20-month lay-off at the 2018 Malaysian Open in July that year. (malaymail.com, 19 Jul 2018; thestar.com.my, 24 Feb 2018; nst.com.my, 18 Dec 2017)She suffered from dengue fever in 2014 but recovered in time to compete at the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, Scotland. (theborneopost.com, 08 Aug 2014)In February 2014 she suffered a thigh injury at the Cleveland Classic event in the United States of America. (thestar.com.my, 23 Feb 2014)'), ('Languages', 'English'), ('Hobbies', 'Coffee, spending time at the beach. (psaworldtour.com, 17 Jul 2018)'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationAsian Games1Team2014Incheon, KOR1Team2010Guangzhou, CHN2Singles2014Incheon, KOR3Singles2010Guangzhou, CHNWorld Games4Singles2013Cali, COLWorld Championships5Singles2014Cairo, EGY5Singles2012Camana Bay, CAY5Singles2011Rotterdam, NED5Singles2010Sharm El Sheikh, EGY17Singles2015Kuala Lumpur, MAS17Singles2008Manchester, GBRWorld Team Championships2Team2014Niagara-on-the-Lake, ON, CAN3Team2012Nimes, FRA3Team2010Palmerston North, NZL3Team2008Cairo, EGYAsian Individual Championships1Team2008Kuwait2Singles2013Islamabad, PAK3Singles2011George Town, MAS3Team2010Chennai, INDWorld Ranking (as of 01 Aug 2018)70Singles2018')]

(timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 09 Apr 2018; SportsDeskOnline, 29 Jul 2018)EARLY DAYSAs she started getting involved in the sport, she found it tough to manage her studies, but her mother offered her support and motivated her to continue with the sport. "It was becoming difficult to manage, I was missing classes. At that time, my school and academy came forward to help me with extra classes and flexible training hours, but still something kept telling me that I need to take a call. So I sat down with my mother telling her that my mind is always on table tennis and I can\'t concentrate on studies as much as I should. It\'s a very tough decision for any child to put studies behind for sports, but my mother supported me entirely." name: HEENA
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began shooting in 2006. (heenasidhu.com, 24 Feb 2018)'), ('Reason', '"My uncle had a business in guns so that was how I was exposed to pistols from my childhood. It was in 2006, while I was preparing for my pre-medical entrance exams that I thought of shooting, just as a hobby. At that time it was only meant as a distraction from a hectic schedule, including hours of studying. I never thought that this is what I would eventually end up doing for the rest of my life. But when I decided to take up shooting my family supported me wholeheartedly. And the rest is history." (heenasidhu.com, 24 Feb 2018)'), ('Debut', '2009 for India, World Cup in Changwon, Republic of Korea (issf-sports.org, 10 Nov 2013)'), ('Coach', 'Ved Prakash Pilaniya [national], IND; Ronak Pandit [husband], IND (firstpost.com, 18 Feb 2018; sportsauthorityofindia.nic.in, 13 Feb 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a medal at the Olympic Games. (Facebook page, 22 Mar 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Being ranked number one in the world in April 2014. (heenasidhu.com, 24 Feb 2018)'), ('Awards', "In February 2018 she was named in the India '30 Under 30' list by the Forbes Magazine. (inuth.com, 05 Feb 2018)In 2014 she was presented with the Arjuna Award by the Indian government. (firstpost.com, 18 Feb 2018)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralSHOOTING CENTREShe and her husband Ronak Pandit, a gold medallist at the 2006 Commonwealth Games in Melbourne, VIC, Australia, have set up shooting centres in Mumbai and Pune in India to promote the sport among young people. "When I started shooting in 2006, there were no coaches who understood the art and science of shooting. I learnt pistol shooting by reading articles and watching videos of elite shooters on the internet. I was fortunate to understand the basics of pistol shooting from these articles and videos, but still I had to make a lot of changes in my technique as I started competing at high levels, mostly because I did not have an experienced coach to guide me as a beginner. Because of the challenges that I faced in the formative years of my shooting career, it was always my dream to help the young talent of this country in understanding the sport of pistol shooting." (heenasidhu.com, 01 Jan 2018) '), ('Relatives', 'Her husband Ronak Pandit competed in shooting for India at the 2006 Commonwealth Games in Melbourne, VIC, Australia. Her father Rajveer, her mother Rominder Kaur and her brother Karanbir have also represented India in shooting. (bhaskar. catchnews.com, 02 Dec 2017; sportscelebfamily.com, 01 Apr 2017)'), ('Education', 'Dentistry - Gian Sagar Medical College, Patiala, IND'), ('Languages', 'English, Hindi, Punjabi'), ('Hobbies', 'Painting, drawing. name: RATCHANOK
bio: [('Beginning', "She was introduced to the sport at age five. Her parents worked in a factory that produced desserts, and she would often spend time there. The factory owners were worried that she could be burned by boiling water and hot sugar so they restricted her to the company's badminton court. (thestar.com, 21 Aug 2013; bwfbadminton.com, 15 Jan 2014)"), ('Reason', '"In the first place, I really didn\'t like it. My parents said that I should give it a try. After a few years I started to love the game and I realised that I could make a living." (firstpost.com, 12 Aug 2013)'), ('Debut', '2009 for Thailand, in Hanoi, Vietnam (badmintoncentral.com, 27 Apr 2009)'), ('Coach', 'Rexy Mainaky [national], INA (juara.bolasport.com, 09 Feb 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win an a gold medal at an Olympic Games and to be number one in the world. (bwfbadminton.com, 15 Jan 2014)'), ('Memorable', "Winning gold in singles at the 2013 World Championships in Guangzhou, People's Republic of China. (bwfbadminton.com, 04 Apr 2018)"), ('Awards', "She was Thailand's flag bearer during the opening ceremony of the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (thestar.com.my, 12 Aug 2016)In 2014 she was named Best Asian Sporting Icon by Fox Sports Asia. (foxsportsasia.com, 17 Jun 2014)She was named 2013 Best Female Amateur Athlete by the Sports Writers' Association of Thailand. (bangkokpost.com, 27 Mar 2014)In 2010 she received the International Olympic Committee [IOC] Inspiring Young People Trophy. (badmintonstar.com, 29 Aug 2013)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralHISTORIC ACHIEVEMENTSHer gold medal in singles at the 2013 World Championships in Guangzhou, People\'s Republic of China, was the first world championship title won by a Thai badminton player. At age 18 years and 187 days, the victory also made her the youngest player at the time from any nation to have won a world singles title, and the second-youngest player from any nation to win a world title in doubles or singles events. (SportsDeskOnline, 11 Jun 2018)OLYMPIC DISAPPOINTMENT TO WORLD CHAMPIONAt the 2012 Olympic Games in London she was winning 16-9 in her quarterfinal match against Chinese player Wang Xin, but failed to convert the advantage into victory. "It was my worst experience as a player." She came back from the disappointment to win a world singles title the following year, which was the first time since 1999 that a female player from a nation other than People\'s Republic of China had won a women\'s world singles title. "After I won [the world title in 2013], I felt the pressure. But a year passed and I felt that I was still human." (sportskeeda.com, 11 Mar 2016) '), ('Hero', 'Chinese badminton player Wang Yihan. (badmintonstar.com, 29 Aug 2013)'), ('Nickname', 'May, Nong May (bangkok.coconuts.co, 18 Apr 2016; thestar.com, 21 Aug 2013)'), ('Injuries', 'After competing at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro, she was out of action for six months due to a knee injury. She returned to competition in March 2017 at the All England Open in Birmingham. (indianexpress.com, 29 Mar 2017)An ankle injury forced her to withdraw from her quarterfinals match at the 2015 All England Open in Birmingham. bio: [('Beginning', 'She began fencing in 1994. (naver.com, 03 Aug 2012)'), ('Reason', 'One of her teachers suggested she try the sport. (newswire.co.kr, 30 Dec 2014) She was named Sport Star of the Year at the 2012 Kyungki Do Sport Awards in the Republic of Korea.
